ll -- long list -- To see the all files and directories permissions

File and Directory Permissions in Linux

In Linux, every file and directory has permissions that control who can read, write, or execute them. These permissions are categorized into three groups:

Owner (User) â€“ The creator of the file/directory.

Group â€“ A set of users who share access.

Others â€“ Everyone else.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Each permission is represented using three characters:

r (read)(4) â†’ View the contents of a file or list a directory.

w (write)(2) â†’ Modify a file or create/delete files in a directory.

x (execute)(1) â†’ Run a file as a program or access a directory.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Permission Representation

Permissions are displayed using ls -l, showing a 10-character string like:


-rw-r--r--  1 user group  1234 Apr 3 10:00 file.txt
Breaking it down:

-rw-r--r--

- â†’ Type (- for file, d for directory)

rw- â†’ Owner has read and write permissions.

r-- â†’ Group has read-only permission.

r-- â†’ Others have read-only permission.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

For directories:

drwxr-xr-x  1 user group  4096 Apr 3 10:00 mydir

d â†’ Directory

rwx â†’ Owner has read, write, and execute permissions.

r-x â†’ Group can read and execute but cannot modify.

r-x â†’ Others can read and execute but cannot modify.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Default Permissions (Umask)

Files: Default is rw-r--r-- (644) because execute (x) is removed.

Directories: Default is rwxr-xr-x (755) because directories need execute (x) for navigation.

You can check the current umask (which determines default permissions) using:

Common umask values:

022 â†’ Files: 644, Directories: 755

666-022=644
777-022=755

